tips<- read.csv("tips.csv")

# histogram
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(data=tips,aes(tip),binwidth=10)+
geom_histogram(fill="white",col="black")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# Density
# It is the continuous and smoothed version of the histogram
# estimated from the data.
# To calculate this, divide the frequency of a group 
# by the width of it.

# density histogram

ggplot(data=tips, aes(x = tip)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.5) +
  geom_density(size=1,col="blue")
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
## ℹ Please use `linewidth` instead.
## Warning: The dot-dot notation (`..density..`) was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
## ℹ Please use `after_stat(density)` instead.

# Normal distribution

# X ~ Normal (mean=mu, variance=sigma^2)
# X ~ Normal (mean=mu=0, variance=sigma^2=1), Standard normal distribution
# Generate data from a normal distribution

# DePauw, N=1600

#rnorm(x, mean=mu, sd=sigma)
round(rnorm(10, mean=21, sd=1),1)
##  [1] 20.9 20.2 20.6 20.3 20.2 21.7 21.5 21.0 20.5 19.7
# Generate age of 1600 students

set.seed(43435)  # choose any numbers
age <- round(rnorm(1600, mean=21, sd=1),1)
# Draw a density histogram

df <- data.frame(age=round(rnorm(1600, mean=21, sd=1),1))
head(df)
##    age
## 1 21.4
## 2 21.0
## 3 22.6
## 4 20.8
## 5 21.0
## 6 20.2
ggplot(data=df, aes(x = age)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.1) +
  geom_density(size=1,col="blue")

# Overlay a normal density curve
# dnorm(x, mean=mu, sd=sigma)
ggplot(data=df, aes(x = age)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.75) +
  geom_density(size=1,col="blue")+
  
  stat_function(fun=dnorm,
               args=list(mean=mean(df$age),
                         sd=sd(df$age)),
               col="red", size=1)
